{{Infobox Artwork | image_file=Correggio - Madonna and Child with Sts Jerome and Mary Magdalen (The Day) - WGA05327.jpg | image_size= 300px | title=Madonna and Child with Sts Jerome and Mary Magdalen (The Day) | artist=[[Antonio Allegri|Correggio]] | year=c. 1528 | medium=[[Oil painting|Oil on canvas]] | height_metric=235 | width_metric=141 | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | museum=[[Galleria Nazionale di Parma|Galleria Nazionale]], [[Parma]] }}
The '''''Madonna and Child with Sts Jerome and Mary Magdalen (The Day)''''' is an [[oil painting|oil on canvas]] painting by the Italian Renaissance artist [[Antonio Allegri|Correggio]] dating from around 1528 and housed in the [[Galleria Nazionale di Parma|Galleria Nazionale]] of [[Parma]], [[Italy]].
==History== The canvas was commissioned in 1523 by Briseide Colla for a private chapel on the right side of the church of [[Sant'Antonio Abate, Parma|Sant'Antonio Abate]] in Parma. Contemporary art historian and painter [[Giorgio Vasari]] described the work's ''il mirabile colorito'' ("wonderful color"), and it was also studied by [[El Greco]].
In the early 18th century, the church needed costly restoration works and several collectors, including the Kings of Poland and France and the [[Holy Roman Emperor]], offered to buy the work. However, in 1749 it was transferred into the [[Cathedral of Parma]] and later was bought by the [[Duchy of Parma]]. During the [[Napoleonic Wars|French occupation of northern Italy]], it was stolen and brought to France. The painting was returned to Italy in 1815 and placed on display in the Parma gallery. A 1724 copy of the painting hangs in the chapel of [[Palais Rohan, Strasbourg]].
