'''Monoethnicity''' is the existence of a single [[ethnic group]] in a given [[region]] or country. It is the opposite of [[polyethnicity]].
[[China]] is the largest monoethnic country; 91.6% of the population are [[Han Chinese]]. An example of a largely monoethnic country is [[Japan]]. It is a common belief in Japan that the entire country is monoethnic, but a few [[Ethnic issues in Japan#Japanese ethnic minorities|ethnic minorities live in Japan]] (e.g. [[Zainichi|Koreans]], [[Ainu people|Ainus]] and [[Ryukyuan people|Ryukyuans]]).<ref>{{Cite book|page=36|title=Refugee Law and Practice in Japan|author=Osamu Arakaki|publisher=[[Ashgate Publishing]]|date=2008|isbn=0754670090}}</ref> They represent around 1% of the whole population.<ref>{{ja icon}} [http://www.moj.go.jp/content/000108878.pdf] {{lang|ja| 平成２４年末現在における外国人登録者統計について}}].</ref>
[[South Korea]]ns regard themselves as a monoethnic society, although there are small ethnic minorities that exist in South Korea, where they account for around 1% of the South Korean population. These include around 650,000 Chinese immigrants.<ref>{{Citation | date = 2009-02-24 | newspaper = The Los Angeles Times | url = http://articles.latimes.com/2009/feb/24/world/fg-korea-teach24 | title = Trying to teach South Korea about discrimination}}.</ref>
Most [[Sub-Saharan African]] countries have what would be considered a mono-[[racial]] society, but it's common to find dozens of ethnic groups within the same country.
The [[Yugoslav Wars]] are noted as having made territories "[[de facto]] and [[de jure]] monoethnic nation-states".<ref name="Dempsey2002">{{cite book|author=Gary Dempsey|title=Exiting the Balkan Thicket|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EG_jyoDpN1EC&pg=PA91|year=2002|publisher=Cato Institute|isbn=978-1-930865-17-4|pages=91–}}</ref>
